\begin_layout Subsection*
Geometric Interpretation of Vectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One day my friend Victor took a 5 kilometer drive.
 When Victor told me this I knew just how long his drive was.
 It was 5 kilometers.
 When Victor added that his drive was on a very straight highway headed
 due east, I knew more.
 I knew which way Victor was driving.
 I could imagine tracing out his path on a map by drawing a horizontal arrow
 pointing to the right (eastward) with a length equivalent to 5 kilometers.
 The arrow captures both the direction and length of Victor's drive.
 Vectors can be imagined in the same way.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
5\\
0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

has a 5 as its first entry and a 0 as its second.
 Thinking of these entries as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

- and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

- coordinates, the five represents 5 units right (eastward) and the zero
 represents 0 units up (northward).
 In this way, the vector represents both the length and direction of Victor's
 drive, just like the arrow.
 The vector and the arrow can be interpreted to represent the same thing,
 blurring any distinction between them.
 
