\begin_layout Standard
Notice there is no origin on the map.
 This is typical of drawing vectors.
 They are not specified relative to an origin.
 They only represent a change in location, or displacement, starting anywhere.
 A vector represents the locations of two points relative to one another.
 Exactly where those two points lie is not determined by the vector itself.
 Further information is needed to locate the vector.
 In the case of Victor's travel, I needed to know on what road and where
 he was driving to create an accurate picture of his drive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After driving 5 kilometers east, Victor exited the highway and drove 3 kilometer
s southeast (using a road that does not appear on the map).
 When I heard this, I was able to capture this part of Victor's journey
 by the vector
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}\\
-\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/theory-linear-vector-transformations-2.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 60

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
And I knew exactly where to put it since it started just where the previous
 leg left off.
 Drawn as an arrow, the vector is the hypotenuse of a right triangle with
 side lengths 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}$
\end_inset

, which by the Pythagorean theorem gives it length 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\left(\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}\right)^{2}+\left(\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}\right)^{2}}=3$
\end_inset

.
 It has the right length and it points southeast (and starts where the first
 leg leaves off), so it accurately represents the second leg of Victor's
 drive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the crow flies, Victor's total displacement or movement for the drive
 is represented by the sum of the vectors,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
5\\
0
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{c}
\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}\\
-\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
5+\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}\\
-\sqrt{\frac{9}{2}}
\end{array}\right],
\]

\end_inset

the black vector in the diagram.
\end_layout

